Art, although I have no idea as to why you seem to take exception with Charles postulation that Stalin and cohorts outside of the USSR borders inflicted greater harm than did Hitler, I would like to give you numbers to give him credence.<br><br>
During Stalin's regime, in 1928, he instituted a &quot;five year plan&quot; to change the state from agrarian to industrialization which caused untold millions of deaths in his own country. Between 1934 to 1938, he instituted a political purge, arresting 18 million. Seven and a half million were executed while the remainder died a hellish death in forced labor camps. The executed victims were the lucky ones.<br><br>
To break down the number of deaths to average yearly numbers seems ludicrous. These numbers are well accepted by the current Russian government and by the western countries. The unacceptable difference is that the Jews have their memorials while those killed in the USSR have not theirs. I would not dispute the 85 million numbers attributed to all the communist regimes.<br><br>
As for books published in foriegn countries, it seems that the logical reason would be the added cost to distribution to foriegn countries. Many books published outside the US only have local interests. I saw no mention by Charles about the book being &quot;banned&quot;.
